"   <div id=\"basicsTopicLeft\">",
"    <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"     Patient information: Early menopause (primary ovarian insufficiency) (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/early-menopause-primary-ovarian-insufficiency-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440333\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is early menopause?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Menopause is the time in a woman&rsquo;s life when she naturally stops having periods. Menopause usually occurs between the ages of 45 and 55. But in some women, menopause comes early &mdash; before the age of 40.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Some women with this condition keep having periods every once in a while. They might even be able to get pregnant. Instead of calling it &ldquo;early menopause,&rdquo; doctors prefer to call it &ldquo;primary ovarian insufficiency&rdquo; (POI). You might also hear the term &ldquo;premature ovarian failure&rdquo; (POF).",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440340\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What causes early menopause?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Early menopause happens when something causes the ovaries to stop working well. Normally, the ovaries release an egg about once a month. This is called &ldquo;ovulation,&rdquo; and it makes pregnancy possible (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef73238 \" href=\"UTD.htm?3/50/3876\">",
"       figure 1",
"      </a>",
"      ).",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      In women with early menopause, the ovaries start running out of eggs. As a result, they might:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Release eggs less often than normal",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Stop releasing eggs completely",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440347\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Why did my ovaries stop working?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Most of the time, doctors don&rsquo;t know what causes early menopause. In some women, causes include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Problems with their genes",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Cancer treatments",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Autoimmune diseases, in which the body attacks its own ovaries",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440354\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of early menopause?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The first thing most women notice is missed periods, or periods that are lighter than normal. Other symptoms you might have are:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Hot flashes, which feel like a wave of heat that starts in your chest and face and then moves through your body",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Extreme sweating at night",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Dryness in your vagina",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Pain during sex",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Trouble sleeping",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440361\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What other symptoms should I watch for?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Certain symptoms can be clues about what is causing your condition. Make sure to tell your doctor if you:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Feel weak or very tired all the time",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Have lost weight without trying",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Have pain in your belly",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Crave salt",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Notice your skin getting darker, even though you have not been out in the sun",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440368\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Should I see a doctor or nurse?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;See your doctor or nurse if you are younger than 40 and your periods have been irregular for at least three months.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440375\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Are there tests I should have?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Your doctor or nurse will decide which tests you should have based on your age, other symptoms, and individual situation. Common tests include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        A pregnancy test",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Blood tests &ndash; These measure hormone levels. They can show why your periods are irregular.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Genetic tests &ndash; If your hormone tests show that you do have early menopause, you will probably have other blood tests that can show if something is wrong with your chromosomes. (Chromosomes are structures in cells that contain thousands of genes.)",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440382\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is early menopause treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;That depends on what is causing your condition. The most common way to treat early menopause is with hormones, such as estrogen. These replace what the ovaries are not making anymore. Hormones will reduce your symptoms, especially hot flashes and night sweats. They will also help protect your bones and maybe your heart. Women usually take hormones until at least age 50.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440389\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What if I want to get pregnant?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;There might still be hope. About 10 percent of women with early menopause are able to have a baby on their own. When women can&rsquo;t get pregnant on their own, they can still get pregnant with new technologies. These methods use eggs that come from another woman.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440396\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What will my life be like?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Learning that you have early menopause can be very emotional. You might feel anxiety, sadness, or grief. Some women worry that they will grow old very fast and die young. This is not true. Tell your doctor about these feelings. It takes time to cope. Therapy and support groups can help. You should also tell your doctor if you want to get pregnant. There might still be options.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H194440403\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       More on this topic",
"      </span>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <a class=\"medical medical_basics\" href=\"UTD.htm?36/4/36930?source=see_link\">",
"       Patient information: Absent or irregular periods (The Basics)",
"      </a>",
"      <br/>",
